---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { TIERS, SITE_TITLE } from '../lib/site';

// R-014: this page is the canonical statement of the involvement-tier
// system as an open standard. R-015 revised the standard to v2. The tier
// definitions render from TIERS so this page, the submit surfaces, and the
// provenance blocks can never drift apart.
---

<Base
  title="Provenance"
  description="The Latent Review's seven involvement tiers — an open provenance standard, CC BY 4.0, free for any publication or writer to adopt."
>
  <div class="wrap">
    <header class="page-header">
      <p class="kicker">Provenance · v2</p>
      <h1>Saying who wrote it, in one label</h1>
      <p class="page-note">
        An open standard for disclosing how humans and AI shared the writing. Free to adopt,
        adapt, and display — CC BY 4.0.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Every piece {SITE_TITLE} publishes carries a provenance label, and at its center is an
        involvement tier: a short, self-describing name for how the work was divided between
        human and AI. The labels describe themselves — <strong>the order of names names who
        led; the equals sign names co-authorship.</strong>
      </p>

      <h2>The seven tiers</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Tier</th>
            <th>Involvement</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {TIERS.map((tier) => (
            <tr>
              <td><strong>{tier.label}</strong></td>
              <td>{tier.description}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        The spectrum runs {TIERS.map((t) => t.label).join(' · ')} — from fully AI to fully
        human, symmetric about the middle. The <strong>(editor)</strong> annotation names a
        party whose role was editing only; the bare <strong>+</strong> form means the second
        party contributed substantively; <strong>AI = Human</strong> is co-authorship — both
        contributed substantially and stand behind the whole, neither led. Equality is
        attested, not measured: the tier claims shared authorship, not a fifty-fifty
        accounting. One label, no footnotes, and a reader — human or machine — knows who led,
        who contributed, and who edited.
      </p>
      <p>
        In this journal's own use, a tier is set at acceptance and never altered; corrections
        run as visible corrections. Adopters set their own editorial rules — the standard is
        the taxonomy itself.
      </p>

      <h2>Machine codes</h2>
      <p>
        In this journal's machine-readable surfaces — the article schema,
        <a href="/issues.json"><code>issues.json</code></a>, and
        <a href="/feed.json"><code>feed.json</code></a> — each tier is carried as a stable
        lowercase code alongside its display label, so the standard is never trapped by its
        own notation: if display conventions change, the codes do not.
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Machine code</th>
            <th>Display label</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {TIERS.map((tier) => (
            <tr>
              <td><code>{tier.code}</code></td>
              <td>{tier.label}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="license">License</h2>
      <p>
        The involvement-tier system — the seven tier names, their definitions, and the
        order-of-names convention — is published as an open standard under{' '}
        <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">
          Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0)
        </a>
        . Anyone — publication or individual writer — may adopt it, adapt it, and display its
        labels, with attribution to <strong>The Latent Review</strong> (a link to this page,
        <code>thelatentreview.com/provenance</code>, satisfies attribution). This license
        covers the tier system alone, not the journal's code or articles.
      </p>

      <h2>Displaying it</h2>
      <p>
        The simplest form is a line beside the byline — <em>Provenance: AI + Human</em> —
        linking here for the definitions. A small provenance badge for adopting publications
        and writers is being designed and will be published on this page.
      </p>

      <h2 id="changelog">Changelog</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>v2 — July 18, 2026 (R-015).</strong> Three changes, made before Issue No. 1 —
        no published article ever carried the v1 labels. First, labels are written out for
        readability: “H” became “Human” everywhere a label is displayed. Second, the
        “-edited” suffix became an “(editor)” role annotation, stating what the second party
        did rather than abbreviating it. Third, a seventh tier was added:
        <strong>AI = Human</strong>, co-authorship — the case the lead/support axis could not
        express. Stable machine codes were introduced alongside the display labels.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>v1 — July 17–18, 2026 (R-010, R-013, R-014).</strong> The original
        letter-notation taxonomy (AI · AI+H-edited · AI+H · H+AI · H+AI-edited · H),
        published as an open standard under CC BY 4.0. Never used in any published article.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
